	<div id="id1ce1" class="post">
		<h2 class="title"><span class="image-wrapper"><img height="45" alt="Leland shares space with The Martha" width="581" class="title" src="../../../resources/net.databinder.components.RenderedLabel/bd06e3f"/><span class="title">Leland shares space with The Martha</span></span></h2>
		<div class="byline"><span>
			<span>By <span class="alias">Leland</span>, <span>on May 23, 2007</span></span>
			
		</span></div>
		<div><p>As a New Yorker with a food blog, I sometimes get invited to food things happening around town, and I try my best to attend if they&#8217;re at all interesting. When I was invited to watch Martha Stewart interview Jean-Georges Vongerichten on <a href="http://www.sirius.com/servlet/ContentServer?pagename=Sirius/CachedPage&#38;c=Channel&#38;cid=1115038982636">Sirius Radio</a> tonight, I sent a breathless <span class="caps">RSVP</span>. Two, actually, in case the first one didn&#8217;t take. I wouldn&#8217;t miss a chance to bask in the Martha glow for anything.</p>


	<p>And bask we all did. She looks gorgeous.</p>


	<p><img src="/pictures/martha1.jpg" alt="" /></p>


	<p>This was the first recording of <em>At Martha&#8217;s Table</em>, a radio program where Martha interviews famous chefs about their background and careers. Hors d&#8217;oeuvre were provided by <a href="http://nymag.com/listings/restaurant/vong/">Vong</a>, and most of them were lovely (all, in fact, except the purses of something bitter and topped with gold leaf, pictured below; even gold couldn&#8217;t save it). Guests started showing up at 6, and we all had a chance to meet and mingle while we waited for her entrance. I got to know the couple behind <a href="http://www.nosheteria.com/">Nosheteria</a>, and I found I had plenty in common with one of <a href="http://kitchen.apartmenttherapy.com/">The Kitchen&#8217;s</a> principal writers.</p>


	<p><img src="/pictures/martha2.jpg" alt="" /></p>


	<p>Martha&#8217;s companies were well represented, and I met all variety of communications people and editors. It was great fun to be in a room full of people with such similar interests. Hostess and interviewee aside, this gathering wasn&#8217;t about celebrity chefs and restaurantsâ€”it was about cooking and eating. Everyone I met was curious about this blog, and about food blogs in general.</p>


	<p>I didn&#8217;t have a chance to meet the woman herself, but what would I have said? I suppose I would have just said thank you, and good luck with your radio show!</p></div>
	</div>
